<p>"The  best way to think of ADD is not as a mental disorder but as a  collection of traits and tendencies that define a way of being in the  world.  There is some positive to it and some negative, some glory and  some pain.  If the negative becomes a disabling, then this way of being  in the world can become a disorder.  The point of diagnosis and  treatment is to transform the disorder into an asset."</p>
<p><em style="font-style: italic;">~ Delivered From Distraction: Getting the Most out of Life with Attention Deficit Disorder, </em></p>
<p>by Edward M. Hallowell, MD, and John J. Ratey, MD</p>
